<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate <m>\int_\cC x^2y^2\,\dee{x}+x^3y\,\dee{y}</m> counterclockwise around
the square with vertices <m>(0,0)</m>, <m>(1,0)</m>, <m>(1,1)</m> and <m>(0,1)</m>.
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
The top and bottom of the square can be easily paramerized using <m>x</m>
as the parameter. The other two sides can be easily parameterized using <m>y</m>
as the parameter.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
<m>\frac{1}{6}</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
The square has four sides, each of which is a line segment.
<ul>
<li>
On the first side, <m>y=0</m> and <m>\dee{y}=0</m>. That is, we may parametrize
the first side by <m>\vr(x)=x\,\hi</m> with <m>0\le x\le 1</m>.
</li>
<li>
On the second side, <m>x=1</m> and <m>\dee{x}=0</m>. We may parametrize
the second side by <m>\vr(y)=\hi+y\,\hj</m> with <m>0\le y\le 1</m>.
</li>
<li>
On the third side, <m>y=1</m> and <m>\dee{y}=0</m>. We may parametrize the
third side by <m>\vr(x)=x\,\hi+\hj</m> with <m>x</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>.
</li>
<li>
On the final side, <m>x=0</m> and <m>\dee{x}=0</m>.  We may parametrize the
fourth side by <m>\vr(y)=y\,\hj</m> with <m>y</m> running from <m>1</m> to <m>0</m>.
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<sidebyside width="30%">
  <image source="pfigs/square"/>
</sidebyside>

<p>
So
<md>
<mrow>
\int_\cC x^2y^2\,\dee{x}+x^3y\,\dee{y}
&amp;=\int_0^1 x^2\times 0^2\,\dee{x} +\int_0^1 1^3\times y\,\dee{y}
+\int_1^0 x^2\times 1^2\,\dee{x}
</mrow><mrow>&amp;\hskip2in+\int_1^0 0^3\times y\,\dee{y}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{3}
=\frac{1}{6}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
For each of the following fields, decide which of the following holds:
<ol marker="A">
<li> The characterization of conservative vector fields, Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screenConserv"/> (with Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screen"/>),  tells us <m>\vF</m> is conservative.
</li>
<li> The characterization of conservative vector fields, Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screenConserv"/> (with Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screen"/>), tells us <m>\vF</m> is <alert>not</alert> conservative.
</li>
<li> The characterization of conservative vector fields, Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screenConserv"/> (with Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screen"/>), does not tell us whether <m>\vF</m> is conservative or not.
</li>
</ol>
</p>

<p><ol marker="a">
<li> <m>\vF=x\hi + z\hj + y\hk</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vF=y^2z\hi + x^2z\hj + x^2y\hk</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vF=(ye^{xy}+1)\hi + (xe^{xy}+z)\hj + \left(z+y\right)\hk</m>
</li>
<li> <m>\vF=y\cos(xy)\hi + x\sin(xy)\hj </m>
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
Contrast Theorems<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screenConserv"/> and <xref ref="thm_screen"/>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
a.  A </p><p>
b.  B </p><p>
c.  A </p><p>
d.  B
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Every <m>\vF</m> in this problem is defined and has continuous first-order partial derivatives on all of <m>\mathbb R^2</m> or <m>\mathbb R^3</m>. The characterization in Theorem<nbsp/><xref ref="thm_screenConserv"/> tells us that our fields will be conservative if and only if they pass the screening test, i.e. have curl 0.
</p>

<p> a.
<md>
<mrow>\vF&amp;=x\hi + z\hj + y\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vnabla \times \vF&amp;=\Big(\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial y} -\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial z} \Big)\hi
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial z} -\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial x} \Big)\hj
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y} \Big)\hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=(1-1)\hi+(0-0)\hj+(0-0)\hk = \mathbf0
</mrow>
</md>
This field passes the screening test.  Since <m>\vF</m> is defined and has continuous first-order partial derivatives on all of <m>\mathbb R^3</m>, it is conservative. So, we have option A.
</p>

<p>  b.
<md>
<mrow>\vF&amp;=y^2z\hi + x^2z\hj + x^2y\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vnabla \times \vF&amp;=\Big(\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial y} -\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial z} \Big)\hi
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial z} -\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial x} \Big)\hj
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y} \Big)\hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=(x^2-x^2)\hi+(y^2-2xy)\hj+(2xz-2yz)\hk \neq \mathbf0
</mrow>
</md>
So, <m>\vF</m> fails the screening test.  So, it's not conservative. That's option B.
</p>

<p> c.
 <md>
<mrow>\vF&amp;=(ye^{xy}+1)\hi + (xe^{xy}+z)\hj + \left( z+y\right)\hk
</mrow><mrow>
\vnabla \times \vF&amp;=\Big(\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial y} -\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial z} \Big)\hi
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial z} -\frac{\partial F_3}{\partial x} \Big)\hj
+\Big(\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x} -\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y} \Big)\hk
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=(1-1)\hi+(0-0)\hj+\{e^{xy}(xy+1)-e^{xy}(xy+1)\}\hk = \mathbf0
</mrow>
</md>
<m>\vF</m> passes the screening test. Since <m>\vF</m> is defined and has continuous first-order partial derivatives on all of <m>\mathbb R^3</m>, it is conservative. So, we have option A.
</p>

<p> d.
 <md>
<mrow>\vF&amp;=y\cos(xy)\hi + x\sin(xy)\hj
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}&amp;=xy\cos(xy)+\sin(xy)
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}&amp;=-xy\sin(xy)+\cos(xy)
</mrow><mrow>
\frac{\partial F_2}{\partial x}&amp;\neq \frac{\partial F_1}{\partial y}
</mrow>
</md>
<m>\vF</m> fails the screening test, so it is not conservative.
That is Option B.
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>\varphi(x,y,z)=e^{x^2+y^2}+\cos(z^2)</m>, and define <m>\vF = \vnabla \varphi</m>. Evaluate <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}</m> over the closed curve <m>C</m> that is an ellipse  traversed clockwise, centred at <m>(1,2,3)</m>, passing through the points <m>(\sqrt5-1,-2,\sqrt5-3)</m>, <m>((\sqrt5-2)/2,-1/2,(\sqrt5-6)/2)</m>, and <m>(-2,\sqrt 3-2,\sqrt3-3)</m>.
</p>

</statement>
<hint><p>
Please don't do any computation, especially not to find <m>C</m>!
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
0
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Since <m>\vF</m> is conservative, <m>\int_C\vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=0</m> over any closed curve <m>C</m>. The given curve is closed, so the integral is simply zero.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Let <m>P_1</m> and <m>P_2</m> be points in <m>\mathbb R^2</m>. Let <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> be paths from <m>P_1</m> to <m>P_2</m>, as shown below.
</p>

<sidebyside width="42%">
<image><latex-image>\begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[ultra thick, blue] plot[smooth, domain=-.79:3.93]({2*sin( \x r)},{2*sin( (\x*2) r)});
\draw[ultra thick, blue,- \gt ] plot[smooth, domain=-.45:-.5]({2*sin( \x r)},{2*sin( (\x*2) r)});
\draw[ultra thick, blue,- \gt ] plot[smooth, domain=3.5:3.45]({2*sin( \x r)},{2*sin( (\x*2) r)});
\draw[ultra thick, blue,- \gt ] plot[smooth, domain=1.6:1.55]({2*sin( \x r)},{2*sin( (\x*2) r)});
\draw[blue] (2.5,0) node{B};
\draw (-1.4,2) node[vertex, label=above:${P_1}$](b){};
\draw (-1.4,-2) node[vertex, label=below:${P_2}$](c){};
\draw[ultra thick, red] (b) to[out=224, in=135] (c);
\draw[red] (-2.25,0) node[left]{A};
\draw[ultra thick, red,- \gt ] (-2.1,1)--(-2.15,.9);
\end{tikzpicture}</latex-image></image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
Suppose <m>\vF</m> is a conservative vector field in <m>\mathbb R^2</m> with <m>\int_A \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=5</m>. What is <m>\int_B \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}?</m>
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
Review properties of conservative vector fields.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
5
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Since <m>\vF</m> is conservative, and <m>A</m> and <m>B</m> start and end at the same points, by path-independence
<m>\int_B \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=\int_A \vF\cdot\dee{\vr}=5.</m>
</p></solution>
